'''Austrian syndrome''' is a medical condition first described by [[Robert Austrian]] in 1957. The classical triad consists of [[pneumonia]], [[endocarditis]], and [[meningitis]], all caused by ''[[Streptococcus pneumoniae]]''. It is associated with [[alcoholism]], due to the presence of [[hyposplenia]] (reduced [[spleen|splenic]] functioning), and can be seen in males between 40 and 60 years old.<ref>Chest. 2009 Nov;136(5 Suppl):e30.</ref>

