[[File:Benzo-a-pyrene.svg|thumb|right|Chemical structure of benzo[a]pyrene|200px]] [[File:Benzo(e)pyrene.png|thumb|right|Chemical structure of benzo[e]pyrene|125px]] A '''benzopyrene''' is an [[organic compound]] with the formula C<sub>20</sub>H<sub>12</sub>. Structurally speaking, the colorless isomers of benzopyrene are pentacyclic hydrocarbons and are fusion products of [[pyrene]] and a [[phenylene|phenylene group]]. Two [[isomer]]ic species of benzopyrene are [[benzo(a)pyrene|benzo[''a'']pyrene]] and the less common [[benzo(e)pyrene|benzo[''e'']pyrene]]. They belong to the chemical class of [[polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon]]s.
==Overview== Related compounds include [[cyclopentapyrenes]], [[dibenzopyrenes]], [[indenopyrenes]] and [[naphthopyrenes]]. Benzopyrene is a component of [[Pitch (resin)|pitch]] and occurs together with other related pentacyclic [[Aromaticity|aromatic]] species such as [[picene]], benzo[[fluoranthene]]s, and [[perylene]].<ref>W. D. Betts "Tar and Pitch" in Kirk‑Othmer Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology, 1997, John Wiley & Sons, New York. {{DOI| 10.1002/0471238961.20011802052020.a01}}</ref> It is naturally emitted by [[forest fire]]s and [[Volcano|volcanic eruptions]] and can also be found in [[coal tar]], [[cigarette smoke]], wood smoke, and burnt foods such as [[coffee]]. Fumes that develop from fat dripping on blistering charcoal are rich in benzopyrene, which can condense on grilled goods.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Larsson |first=B. K. |year=1983 |title=Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons in grilled food |journal=J Agric Food Chem |volume=31 |issue=4 |pages=867–873 |pmid=6352775 |doi=10.1021/jf00118a049 |last2=Sahlberg |first2=GP |last3=Eriksson |first3=AT |last4=Busk |first4=LA}}</ref>
Benzopyrenes are harmful because they form carcinogenic and mutagenic [[metabolite]]s (such as [[(+)-Benzo(a)pyrene-7,8-dihydrodiol-9,10-epoxide|(+)-benzo[''a'']pyrene-7,8-dihydrodiol-9,10-epoxide]] from benzo[''a'']pyrene) which [[intercalation (biochemistry)|intercalate]] into DNA, interfering with [[Transcription (genetics)|transcription]]. They are considered [[pollutants]] and carcinogens. The mechanism of action of benzo[a]pyrene-related DNA modification has been investigated extensively and relates to the activity of cytochrome P450 subclass 1A1 ([[Cytochrome P450, family 1, member A1|CYP1A1]]).<ref>{{cite journal |last=Uno |first=S. |year=2006 |title=Oral Benzo[a]pyrene in Cyp1 knockout mouse lines: CYP1A1 important in detoxication, CYP1B1 metabolism required for immune damage independent of total-body burden and clearance rate|journal=Mol. Pharmacol. |volume=69 |issue=4 |pages=1103–1112 |pmid=16377763 |doi=10.1124/mol.105.021501 |last2=Dalton |first2=TP |last3=Dragin |first3=N |last4=Curran |first4=CP |last5 = Derkenne |first5=S |last6 = Miller |first6=ML |last7 = Shertzer |first7=HG |last8 = Gonzalez |first8=FJ |last9 = Nebert |first9=DW}}</ref> Seemingly, the high activity of CYP1A1 in the intestinal mucosa prevents major amounts of ingested benzo[a]pyrene from entering portal blood and systemic circulation.<ref>{{cite journal|last1 = Uno|first1 = S.|last2 = Dragin|first2 = N.|last3 = Miller|first3 = M. L.|last4 = Dalton|first4 = T. P.|first5 = F. J.|last5 = Gonzalez|last6 = Nebert|first6 = D. W.|year = 2008|title = Basal and Inducible CYP1 mRNA Quantitation and Protein Localization throughout the Mouse Gastrointestinal Tract|journal = [[Free Radical Biology and Medicine]]|volume = 44|issue = 4|pages = 570–583|pmid = 17997381|doi = 10.1016/j.freeradbiomed.2007.10.044|pmc=2754765}}</ref> The intestinal (but not hepatic) detoxification mechanism seems to depend on receptors that recognize bacterial surface components ([[TLR2]]).<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Do| first = KN |last2=Fink|first2=LN |last3=Jensen |first3=TE |last4=Gautier |first4=L | last5=Parlesak |first5=A|year=2012 |title = TLR2 controls intestinal carcinogen detoxication by CYP1A1 | journal = PLoS ONE| volume = 7 | issue = 3 | pages = e32309 | publisher = | location = | url = http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0032309 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0032309 | id = | accessdate = | pmid =22442665| editor1-last = Lebedeva| editor1-first = Irina V| pmc = 3307708 |bibcode=2012PLoSO...732309D}}</ref>
Evidence exists to link benzo[''a'']pyrene to the formation of [[lung cancer]].<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1126/science.274.5286.430 | title = Preferential Formation of Benzo[a]pyrene Adducts at Lung Cancer Mutational Hotspots in P53 | year = 1996 | last1 = Denissenko | first1 = M. F. | last2 = Pao | first2 = A. | last3 = Tang | first3 = M.-s. | last4 = Pfeifer | first4 = G. P. | journal = Science | volume = 274 | issue = 5286 | pages = 430–2 | pmid = 8832894| bibcode = 1996Sci...274..430D }}</ref>
In February 2014, [[NASA]] announced a [http://www.astrochem.org/pahdb/ greatly upgraded database] for tracking polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs), including benzopyrene, in the [[universe]]. According to scientists, more than 20% of the [[carbon]] in the universe may be associated with PAHs, possible [[PAH world hypothesis|starting materials]] for the [[Abiogenesis#PAH world hypothesis|formation]] of [[Life#Extraterrestrial life|life]]. PAHs seem to have been formed shortly after the [[Big Bang]], are widespread throughout the universe, and are associated with [[Star formation|new stars]] and [[exoplanets]].<ref name="NASA-20140221">{{cite web |last=Hoover |first=Rachel |title=Need to Track Organic Nano-Particles Across the Universe? NASA's Got an App for That |url=http://www.nasa.gov/ames/need-to-track-organic-nano-particles-across-the-universe-nasas-got-an-app-for-that/ |date=February 21, 2014 |work=[[NASA]] |accessdate=February 22, 2014 }}</ref>
